<Author>DiningDemon
<Content>A Disappointing Hotel: Satisfactory at Best The high ranking of the Senator Gran Via by Trip Advisor members, as well as its four star status, had encouraged us to expect much of this hotel. In fact it's no better than satisfactory while having some very good features. Essentially the hotel lacks character and is unlikely to make a great impression on most guests. Amongst the hotels better features is its central location. The Plaza Mayor and most other major attractions are a few minutes walk. Also, the hotel can be reached with relative ease by tube direct from the airport. It is only necessary to change trains twice and the Gran Via station is directly in front of the hotel entance. Given that the cost of a tube trip is a fraction of the cost of a taxi this is certainly the best way to reach the hotel, providing of course that you are not encumbered by too many heavy suitcases. The hotel lobby is decidedly cramped and utilitarian in appearance. As such it makes for an inauspicious first impresson. We were allocated a room on the third floor which proved rather smaller than we had anticipated. It was also very spartan in appearance, having a single picture on one wall and apart from cigarette burned translucent drapes, just one curtain. This peculiar arrangement allowed a considerable amount of light from the street to flood into the room at night, making it difficult to sleep. There was room for a single chair to one side of the bed but little else. My partner complained of a smell of cigarette smoke in the bathroom. Shortly after this we discovered that we had been given a room on a smoking floor. Had we been informed of this at the time of checking in we would certainly have requested a room elsewhere. However, since it was by this point late and we had already unpacked we opted to stay put. Based on this experience I would urge non-smoking guests to stipulate that they require a room on a non-smoking floor, both when booking the accommodation and on checking in. The TV provided one English speaking channel: CNN. The bathroom was relatively large -a little tired looking certainly and equipped with decidedly thin and less than fresh looking towels. Yes, the free mini-bar was a welcome and unusual feature. It scarcely made up for some of the shortcomings described above, however. The buffet breakfast, served in the basement, is adequate. The selection is by no means large. It offers what you would typically expect in a three star continental hotel. A member of staff will cook eggs to order though the egg counter was, in our experience, frequently left unattended.The hotel staff we found to be consistently polite and friendly. They greeted us as we passed them in the lobby and were most courteous and helpful when we booked transport for our return journey to the airport. It is worth noting that the hotel is situated on the corner of Gran Via and Calle de la Montera, a major route for pedestrians into the centre of old Madrid. Unfortunately, this road is transformed into an avenue of prostitutes from the early evening onwards.All things considered we found the Senator Gran Via something of a disappointment. There must surely be better hotels at this price elsewhere in the city. 
