<Author>sadblue
<Content>Great Hotel Having read the excellent reviews of the Senator Gran Via on Trip Advisor my wife and I stayed at the hotel for three nights at the end of November 2007 whilst staying in Madrid for the Bruce Springsteen concert. All I can say is that the reviews do not do the hotel justice. As advised in Trip Advisor reviews we asked for a room on the upper floors and paid the extra tariff for a superior room, which is something I would highly recommend. The room we were allocated was on the 6th floor and, as it was a corner room, had a balcony that must have been 50-60 feet long giving great views across the rooftops and down to the streets below. One point to note is that the sound insulation is excellent, we heard no noise from within the hotel and with the windows closed even at the busiest of times no traffic noise could be heard.The hotel itself was spotlessly clean and the staff helpful and friendly. Arrival and checkout were both dealt with ease, our luggage was taken to the room upon arrival and stored following checkout until we left the city, when a cab was hailed within seconds of our requesting one. A glass of Cava (or juice and water) was always waiting next to reception and the mini bar (yes it really is free!!!) was well stocked with beer, soda's  water and was restocked every day. Breakfast was served in the pleasant basement restaurant and I can honestly say that I haven't seen a greater or better selection of food anywhere in the world. There was something to suit all tastes: fruit, cereal, cheeses, cold meats and my favourite, the egg counter which served freshly made eggs or omelettes of your choice. The hotel was centrally located within easy walking distance of all the major sights, shops and museums. One location we found ourselves returning to each day was Plaza Santa Ana. It is a small and lively square lined with bars and cafes, nearly all of which served a fine selection of tapas. We quickly picked up on the fact that the locals spend their evenings on a 'tapas crawl', having one glass of wine and a plate of tapas in each bar. This is obviously not something that tourists indulge in as we got surprised looks every time we ordered just one dish. Another tip, don't be put off by the look of some of the bars, we found that the 'rougher' they looked the better both the tapas and staff were. Finally, don't be put off by reviews mentioning the local 'ladies'. Yes they ply their trade on an adjacent street but they don't come near the hotel and unless you are a single man walking alone they are unlikely to pay you any attention at all.If you are looking for a great hotel in the great city of Madrid, look no further than the Gran Via, I would have no hesitation in staying there again or recommending it to anyone. 
