<Author>A TripAdvisor Member
<Content>Great Hotel In Madrid We stayed at the Hotel Senator Gran Via for three nights beginning June 1, 2006. We were given a room on the fifth floor 鈥?a no smoking floor 鈥?that was both fairly large and very comfortable. Although the Gran Via bustles until all hours (really, they do party until 4:00 AM on Friday and Saturday nights) and our room fronted on the street, the windows combined with the drapes make the room VERY soundproof. The beds were two singles 鈥?that were able to be individually reclined 鈥?that butted together making a king. They were quite comfortable (although I we do not find hard beds a problem). The bathroom was very well equipped and the water pressure was outstanding and hot water was plentiful. The TV did get CNN in English and an English sports broadcast.The complimentary mini-bar was a great feature and it was replenished daily. The hotel鈥檚 staff was very efficient and even surprised us with a bottle of champagne for my wife鈥檚 birthday! When we called down to ask who had sent this to her - we figured friends or one of our kids - the desk manager replied 鈥淚sn鈥檛 it your birthday? Happy birthday from the hotel!鈥?They apparently saw it was her birthday from her passport. Yes, the hotel is right next to the 鈥榬ed light鈥?district. However, the girls were not pushy nor did they bother us in any way. I would definitely recommend this hotel to all except those who might have younger kids that might be put out a bit by the presence of the hookers and the sex shops that were about a block away. Couple of things we experienced: Madrid is a very clean city. The streets are always swept and there is no trash around at all, even in the older areas of town. We did our best to try and engage waiters, service people or shop owners into conversation and struck out except at the hotel. People in Madrid obviously do not care for Americans very much. I can speak enough Spanish to order a meal or handle simple transactions so it wasn鈥檛 as if we were being ugly Americans in Europe. My wife鈥檚 60th birthday low point was actually being spit on by a bum in the Metro after being called an American -----. True, the guy was a nut case but the sentiment was obvious. Maybe people in Madrid don鈥檛 like anyone. And, just so you know where we are coming from, we find the people in France, even in Paris, to be pleasant if not gracious. Don鈥檛 expect a very good meal at any of the restaurants on the Plaza Mayor 鈥?they are best for a drink and a couple of Tapas plates. They are also very expensive.The Palacio Real is truly amazing to see. And, the outdoor tables at the Caf茅 Oriente right across the street from the Palacio Real are wonderful places for drinks, people watching and they serve a good salad. We also had a wonderful dinner at the outdoor portion of a restaurant located in an alley between the Calle Mayor and Calle Arenal called Chiky鈥檚. I鈥檇 recommend it highly. We went to the El Rastro flea market on Sunday. Mostly it鈥檚 t-shirts and sunglasses and other new junk, but it was fun and there were a couple of booths with nice hand-painted pottery and a few with nice items for sale. Again, the sales people in the booths were very 鈥?well, the nicest way I can put it is 鈥?rude. And be careful, my brother-in-law did have his wallet lifted even though he had it in his front pocket and was trying to be careful. We did the one-day trip to Avila and Segovia (72 Euros each with 鈥榞astronomic鈥?lunch included). The trip was great and I would recommend it highly 鈥?but I would pass on the lunch. The restaurant was indoors and crammed with tourists eating roasted pigs. There are lots of places in Segovia that are nice outdoor cafes that would have been much better. The guide was bilingual in Spanish and English and was very good.As far as getting back and forth into the city from the airport is concerned, I would recommend AeroCity ( --- ) The fare for four persons in a mini-van was a total of 22 Euros each way and the drivers were prompt and actually quite pleasant compared to the rest of the people we encountered in Madrid. All in all I have conflicting feelings about Madrid. I liked the city鈥檚 vibrancy, its somewhat schizophrenic architecture and its climate in June. But the people left us cold 鈥?so much so that I probably wouldn鈥檛 return. That鈥檚 too bad because if I did, I would stay again at the Senator Gran Via. 
